  "name": "2 Corinthians 12:1–10",
  "localizedName": "2 Corinthians 12:1–10",
  "content": [
    {
      "tiptap": {
        "type": "doc",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Paul talked about a believer who had a "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108296",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "vision"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " from God. God showed this person things in the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108529",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "heavenly world"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". Then Paul told his readers that the believer was in fact himself."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The false teachers and super-apostles bragged about the visions they had. They used their visions as proof that they were better than Paul. But Paul didn’t brag about his vision."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Paul had a problem that caused him pain and suffering. It made him weak in his body. He didn’t say what this problem was. Paul prayed and asked God to take the problem away. But God chose not to take it away. Instead Jesus comforted Paul by making it clear that he was with him. Jesus’ grace helped Paul to keep going. Whether or not God’s work was done didn’t depend on Paul’s abilities. It depended on the power of Jesus."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
